4. Plot and Understand the distribution of the variable "price per lb" using displot, and write your findings.¶

In [14]:
sns.displot(data["priceperlb"],bins=7,color="#107",kde=True)
plt.title("Distribution Plot for price per lb ")
plt.show()
  • It is positively skewed.
  • Most of the price that is priceperlb ranges between 0.5 and 2.0

5.Plot and understand the relationship between the variables 'numcol' and 'prodval' through scatterplot, and wite your findings¶

In [121]:
sns.scatterplot(x=data["numcol"],y=data["prodvalue"],hue=data["year"],data=data,color=["red"])
plt.show()

It shows a positive relationship.When the numcol increases, prodvalue is also linearly increasing.

6. Plot and understand the relationship between categorical variable 'year' and a numerical variable 'prodvalue' through boxplot, and write your findings.¶

In [178]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,7))
sns.boxplot(data=data,x=data["year"],y=data["prodvalue"],width=0.8)
plt.show()

In every year there is a specific amount of honey is produced within a specific range..

7. Visualize and understand the relationship between the multiple pairs of variables throughout different years using pairplot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol', 'total prod', 'prodvalue','year')¶

In [164]:
sns.pairplot(data=data, hue='year', vars=['numcol', 'yieldpercol','totalprod','prodvalue'])
plt.show()
  • There is a relationship between totalprod and prodvalue.
  • There is a relationship between prodvalue and numcol.
  • There is a relationship between totalprod and numcol.

  • There is a negative correlation between yieldpercol and priceperlb.
  • There is a zero correlation between year and numcol.
